Investors in your offering will purchase Units of Profit Participation Rights issued by your Company. The Company will make distributions from its cash flow to the Holders of Units (i.e. the Investors) on a schedule that will be defined by you on this page and then described by the Matrix in the Private Placement Memorandum for your offering. The schedule may consist of any or all of the following distribution points: annually, upon completion of a refinance, upon sale of the Property. The following terms will be used in the schedule of distributions: 1) Annual Cash Flow. The total cash receipts by the Company during the calendar year (excluding funds invested by the Holders of Profit Participation Rights and any capital contributions by the Members of the Company), plus any other funds (including amounts designated as reserves by the Managing Member, where and to the extent he no longer regards such reserves as reasonably necessary to the efficient conduct of the Company’s business) less (a) any operating expenses of the Company but excluding any expense not involving a cash expenditure, such as amounts charged for depreciation; (b) all payments of principal and interest on account of any loans secured by property of the Company or any other obligations or loans of the Company; (c) Refinance Proceeds or Sale Proceeds that are otherwise distributable; and (d) reserves for working capital and anticipated expenditures in such amounts as may be determined from time to time by the Managing Member. 2) Sale Proceeds. The proceeds received from sale of the Property less a reserve for all accrued expenses of the Company. 3) Return on Investment ("ROI"). Average annual distribution by the Company to an Investor divided by amount Investor invested. 4) Cumulative ROI. ROI measured over multiple years, with shortfalls in one or more years being made up in subsequent years. Here are a few suggestions regarding your schedule:  You should avoid scheduling a greater annual distribution than you can safely expect to make. The same investor who will be unhappy if you schedule a 12% ROI but can only pay 10%, will be happy if you schedule 9% and pay 9%. • The more you promise to allocate to the Investors, the easier it will be the attract Investors. Property law in Pakistan covers the legal structure and regulations regarding property ownership, transfer, and disputes. It includes deciding, registering, buying, selling, renting or transferring residential, commercial, agricultural or industrial properties. 

The Transfer of Property Act, 1882 is the primary legislation governing the transfer of property in Pakistan. It includes guidelines regarding the sale of the property, mortgage, exchange, leases, gifts, and actionable claims.

Also, the Land Acquisition Act of 1894 governs compulsory acquisition or purchase of land and Compensation to be paid. Provincial laws, like The Punjab Partition of Immovable Property Act 2012, also provide rules for partition of joint property. 

Property disputes are resolved by civil courts. Issues like fraudulent property transactions, illegal possession, or inheritance disputes come under the ambit of property law in Pakistan. 

Besides these, the Stamp Act 1899 and Registration Act 1908 play a significant role in property transactions as they require property documents to be registered and stamped to ensure authenticity. 

Islamic principles also have a significant influence on property law, particularly in matters of inheritance. For instance, Pakistani law follows Islamic guidelines for the distribution of an individual's property after their death.

Nevertheless, like all legal matters, property law in Pakistan can be complex, and consulting with a legal professional or an advocate for detailed advice or representation is recommended.

1. Ordovician-Silurian Extinction: This event, occurring approximately 443 million years ago, was the first mass extinction and resulted in an estimated 86% of all species being wiped out. The main cause is believed to be a period of glaciation followed by warming, which dramatically changed the planet's oceans and atmosphere.

2. Late Devonian Extinction: Happening around 359 million years ago, this event saw a loss of approximately 75% of all species. It is speculated to have been caused by a series of climate variations, possibly triggered by asteroid impacts or massive volcanic eruptions. 

3. Permian-Triassic Extinction, or the "Great Dying": This is the largest extinction event, occurring about 252 million years ago and killing off an estimated 96% of all marine species and 70% of terrestrial vertebrate species. The cause of this event is still highly debated, but many scientists believe it was triggered by massive volcanic eruptions in what is now Siberia.

4. Triassic-Jurassic Extinction: Around 201 million years ago, this event caused about 50% of all species to go extinct, clearing the path for dinosaurs to become the dominant species on Earth. Similar to the Permian-Triassic event, it's believed that a series of enormous volcanic eruptions, this time in the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province, was the primary cause.

5. Cretaceous-Paleogene Extinction: This event occurred 66 million years ago when an asteroid about 6 miles in diameter hit what is now Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. This was the event that wiped out the dinosaurs, along with around 75% of all species on Earth. Large volcanic eruptions in what is now India may have contributed to the extinction event.

The Company will make distributions from its cash flow to the Holders of Units (i.e. the Investors) on a schedule that will be defined by you on this page and then described by the Matrix in the Private Placement Memorandum for your offering. The schedule may consist of any or all of the following distribution points: annually, upon completion of a refinance, upon sale of the Property. The following terms will be used in the schedule of distributions: 1) Annual Cash Flow. The total cash receipts by the Company during the calendar year (excluding funds invested by the Holders of Profit Participation Rights and any capital contributions by the Members of the Company), plus any other funds (including amounts designated as reserves by the Managing Member, where and to the extent he no longer regards such reserves as reasonably necessary to the efficient conduct of the Company’s business) less (a) any operating expenses of the Company but excluding any expense not involving a cash expenditure, such as amounts charged for depreciation; (b) all payments of principal and interest on account of any loans secured by property of the Company or any other obligations or loans of the Company; (c) Refinance Proceeds or Sale Proceeds that are otherwise distributable; and (d) reserves for working capital and anticipated expenditures in such amounts as may be determined from time to time by the Managing Member. 2) Sale Proceeds. The proceeds received from sale of the Property less a reserve for all accrued expenses of the Company. 3) Return on Investment ("ROI"). Average annual distribution by the Company to an Investor divided by amount Investor invested. 4) Cumulative ROI. ROI measured over multiple years, with shortfalls in one or more years being made up in subsequent years. Here are a few suggestions regarding your schedule:  You should avoid scheduling a greater annual distribution than you can safely expect to make. questions.question: Investors in your offering will purchase Units of Profit Participation Rights issued by your Company. The Company will make distributions from its cash flow to the Holders of Units (i.e. the Investors) on a schedule that will be defined by you on this page and then described by the Matrix in the Private Placement Memorandum for your offering. The schedule may consist of any or all of the following distribution points: annually, upon completion of a refinance, upon sale of the Property. The following terms will be used in the schedule of distributions: 1) Annual Cash Flow. The total cash receipts by the Company during the calendar year (excluding funds invested by the Holders of Profit Participation Rights and any capital contributions by the Members of the Company), plus any other funds (including amounts designated as reserves by the Managing Member, where and to the extent he no longer regards such reserves as reasonably necessary to the efficient conduct of the Company’s business) less (a) any operating expenses of the Company but excluding any expense not involving a cash expenditure, such as amounts charged for depreciation; (b) all payments of principal and interest on account of any loans secured by property of the Company or any other obligations or loans of the Company; (c) Refinance Proceeds or Sale Proceeds that are otherwise distributable; and (d) reserves for working capital and anticipated expenditures in such amounts as may be determined from time to time by the Managing Member. 2) Sale Proceeds. The proceeds received from sale of the Property less a reserve for all accrued expenses of the Company. 3) Return on Investment ("ROI"). Average annual distribution by the Company to an Investor divided by amount Investor invested. 4) Cumulative ROI. ROI measured over multiple years, with shortfalls in one or more years being made up in subsequent years. Here are a few suggestions regarding your schedule:  You should avoid scheduling a greater annual distribution than you can safely expect to make. The same investor who will be unhappy if you schedule a 12% ROI but can only pay 10%, will be happy if you schedule 9% and pay 9%. • The more you promise to allocate to the Investors, the easier it will be the attract Investors. questions.question: Investors in your offering will purchase Units of Profit Participation Rights issued by your Company. The Company will make distributions from its cash flow to the Holders of Units (i.e. the Investors) on a schedule that will be defined by you on this page and then described by the Matrix in the Private Placement Memorandum for your offering. The schedule may consist of any or all of the following distribution points: annually, upon completion of a refinance, upon sale of the Property. The following terms will be used in the schedule of distributions: 1) Annual Cash Flow. The total cash receipts by the Company during the calendar year (excluding funds invested by the Holders of Profit Participation Rights and any capital contributions by the Members of the Company), plus any other funds (including amounts designated as reserves by the Managing Member, where and to the extent he no longer regards such reserves as reasonably necessary to the efficient conduct of the Company’s business) less (a) any operating expenses of the Company but excluding any expense not involving a cash expenditure, such as amounts charged for depreciation; (b) all payments of principal and interest on account of any loans secured by property of the Company or any other obligations or loans of the Company; (c) Refinance Proceeds or Sale Proceeds that are otherwise distributable; and (d) reserves for working capital and anticipated expenditures in such amounts as may be determined from time to time by the Managing Member. 2) Sale Proceeds. The proceeds received from sale of the Property less a reserve for all accrued expenses of the Company. 3) Return on Investment ("ROI"). Average annual distribution by the Company to an Investor divided by amount Investor invested. 4) Cumulative ROI. ROI measured over multiple years, with shortfalls in one or more years being made up in subsequent years. Here are a few suggestions regarding your schedule:  You should avoid scheduling a greater annual distribution than you can safely expect to make. The same investor who will be unhappy if you schedule a 12% ROI but can only pay 10%, will be happy if you schedule 9% and pay 9%. • The more you promise to allocate to the Investors, the easier it will be the attract Investors. questions.question: Investors in your offering will purchase Units of Profit Participation Rights issued by your Company. The Company will make distributions from its cash flow to the Holders of Units (i.e. the Investors) on a schedule that will be defined by you on this page and then described by the Matrix in the Private Placement Memorandum for your offering. The schedule may consist of any or all of the following distribution points: annually, upon completion of a refinance, upon sale of the Property. The following terms will be used in the schedule of distributions: 1) Annual Cash Flow. The total cash receipts by the Company during the calendar year (excluding funds invested by the Holders of Profit Participation Rights and any capital contributions by the Members of the Company), plus any other funds (including amounts designated as reserves by the Managing Member, where and to the extent he no longer regards such reserves as reasonably necessary to the efficient conduct of the Company’s business) less (a) any operating expenses of the Company but excluding any expense not involving a cash expenditure, such as amounts charged for depreciation; (b) all payments of principal and interest on account of any loans secured by property of the Company or any other obligations or loans of the Company; (c) Refinance Proceeds or Sale Proceeds that are otherwise distributable; and (d) reserves for working capital and anticipated expenditures in such amounts as may be determined from time to time by the Managing Member. 2) Sale Proceeds. The proceeds received from sale of the Property less a reserve for all accrued expenses of the Company. 3) Return on Investment ("ROI"). Average annual distribution by the Company to an Investor divided by amount Investor invested. 4) Cumulative ROI. ROI measured over multiple years, with shortfalls in one or more years being made up in subsequent years. Here are a few suggestions regarding your schedule:  You should avoid scheduling a greater annual distribution than you can safely expect to make. The same investor who will be unhappy if you schedule a 12% ROI but can only pay 10%, will be happy if you schedule 9% and pay 9%. • The more you promise to allocate to the Investors, the easier it will be the attract Investors.
